Doc,<br><br>
This whole issue can be a little profound.  If it was clear we would have no problems.  Ed and I shared a single snapshot from my past and there are too many.  Thread 111<br><br>
You see others on this site feel pain and I don't feel any and I know I should.  Fear was no longer an issue it just wasn't there.  A taste of self destructive desire always lurking just at the conscious level.  I faced death too many times to give a shit.  Normal?  I really have my doubts.  Like I said I heard and saw too much for too long.<br><br>
I will share the last time I wanted to let it go.  My best friend did the dumbest thing.  He invited to me to meet him after mission and get really messed up.  A real buddy, hell his fahter flew with Chenault in China.  While I am standing on the tarmac he comes back with his ass on fire and blows himself to bits right in front of my face.<br><br>
Can you imagine watching a rolling fireball of lifeless metal hurtling along the ground and knowing you friend was no longer there.  I swear I could feel the chill of his spirit pass me as the concussion pushed me back.  Really hurt.<br><br>
The real pain came when the family asked me to bring him back for burial.  I stood on a lonely Mississippi hillside in a slow rain with his fiancee hanging around my neck sobbing and asking why.  To top this the honor guard was firing.  The bugler begin to play taps and I died.  You see Doc the one order you get is be strong for the family.  You can't break, not for an instant.<br><br>
His father had told me the day we pinned our wings on that he would die.  He told me then to lived a full life and bring him home when the time come.  If you think that can't suck your soul dry you would have to be there.<br><br>
Then back to business<br><br>
Nam or any other conflict never felt like much after that.  That is the first of many that ensured I never let my emotions surface.  I couldn't afford the luxury.<br><br>
Well Doc are you sure you can go down memory lane with a guy like me.  I would like to feel deeply again.  Cold is what I have been called.  Even when I was caught in booby trap I felt nothing. ( another story another time).  I couldn't even cry at my grandfathers funeral and he was the most important man in my life.<br><br>
Now What Doc?
